Title: AI Stocks Slip As Microsoft & Google Earnings Disappoint Investors
Description:
AI Stocks Slip As Microsoft & Google Earnings Disappoint Investors 

Artificial Intelligence-related stocks saw a significant downturn yesterday, wiping out $190 billion in the US market value, following underwhelming earnings reports from major players. Google-parent Alphabet saw a 5.6% drop in shares after ad revenue missed forecasts, emphasising the high cost of AI competitiveness. Microsoft, though surpassing revenue forecasts, faced a 1% share dip due to anticipated substantial capital costs for AI infrastructure. Chipmaker AMD also fell 6% as its first-quarter revenue forecast fell short of expectations. Elsewhere in Asia, Samsung shares declined over 1%, after reporting a 34% drop in Q4 profit.

Netflix's Upcoming Avatar: The Last Airbender Series Excites Fans with Authentic Action and Casting
Description:
In mid-January, the energetic phrase "Boomerang's flying!" echoed on the set of Netflix's highly anticipated "Avatar: The Last Airbender" adaptation at Sunset Bronson Studios. Stunt coordinator Jeff Aro, alongside the vibrant cast, including Gordon Cormier (Aang), Kiawentiio (Katara), Dallas Liu (Zuko), and Ian Ousley (Sokka), brought to life the iconic martial arts-inspired action of the beloved fantasy series.

The series, set to premiere on February 22, is a reimagining of the original 2005 Nickelodeon animated show, which captivated audiences with its unique blend of elemental bending powers and profound themes. Showrunner Albert Kim, known for his work as an EW editor, and actor Daniel Dae Kim, playing Ozai, bring a fresh perspective to the live-action adaptation, promising to maintain the spirit of the original while offering a deeper, more mature narrative.

The show's dedication to authentic casting, featuring entirely Asian and Indigenous actors, marks a significant shift from Hollywood's past missteps, like the 2010 movie adaptation criticized for its casting and narrative choices. The Netflix series aims to bridge generational gaps, appealing to both original fans and new audiences, with its enhanced visual effects and a more dramatic series format.

As filming progressed, the cast, including talented newcomers and seasoned actors, developed a profound connection with their characters, embracing the physical and emotional depth required for their roles. This adaptation seeks to explore untold stories and unseen character interactions, enriching the Avatar universe.

The anticipation for this series underscores the lasting impact of the Avatar franchise, which has expanded beyond television to include books, comics, and video games. With its upcoming release, Netflix's "Avatar: The Last Airbender" stands as a testament to the enduring appeal of this imaginative and culturally rich world.

Pineville police responded to a reported shooting at the Walmart on Pineville-Matthews Road around 6:30 p.m. on Jan. 28. When officers arrived, they found an employee who had been shot in the leg and learned that the whole incident apparently started over a self-checkout dispute.

Shooter at Anniston, Alabama  #Walmart #breakingnews #Alabama #viral #shorts
Description:
In a critical incident at the Lenlock Walmart in Anniston, AL, two patrons engaged in a heated disagreement, leading to one brandishing a firearm and firing at least three rounds. No injuries were reported.

Multiple law enforcement agencies, including the Anniston Police Department, Weaver Police Department, Jacksonville Police Department, ATF, FBI, and Major Crime Taskforce, along with the Anniston Fire Department and EMS, swiftly responded. As of now, no arrests have been made, and the alleged shooter fled the scene.

The Anniston Special Response Team conducted a thorough building search, ensuring no victims or suspects remained inside. Authorities state that this wasn't a random act of violence, and there's no apparent threat to the public. The motive and identities are central to the ongoing investigation.

Local residents and Walmart patrons were reassured of no immediate danger, and the Anniston Police Department is committed to a comprehensive understanding of the incident. Authorities urge anyone with information to come forward, and the community is advised to stay updated on official announcements for the latest information.

Kambria Gabrielle Darby, 26, was arrested in the car park of the store inÂ Byram,Â Mississippi, a suburb of Jackson, about 10.30am on January 17.

The two-year-old boy was still 'freezing and shaking' even after another shopper bought him a long-sleeved shirt and pants and dressed him in the store.

Police put the boy in a warm car and called paramedics to assess him. Child Protective Services later took him away and released him to a relative, along with his two siblings.

Darby was charged with contributing to the neglect or delinquency of a child and booked into Hinds County Detention Center.

For the fifth day in a row, the Nasdaq and S&P 500 close higher as Netflix shares rise.

The S&P 500 increased on Wednesday as Netflix spearheaded a larger rise among internet companies, achieving unprecedented heights for the market as a whole.

By gaining just 0.08% to close at 4,868.55, the benchmark S&P 500 set a new closing record. The tech boom helped the Nasdaq Composite rise 0.36% to 15,481.92. For both, it was their sixth day in a row of victory.

A day after each company released its profits, the Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 99.06 points, or 0.26%, to 37,806.39, as a result of losses of more than 2% in Verizon and 3M.

After the streamer revealed that Netflix had reached an all-time high of 260.8 million subscribers, the company's shares increased by more than 10%. Both the revenue and the current-quarter earnings projection exceeded analysts' predictions.

According to Allianz Investment Management senior strategist Charlie Ripley, the earnings announcement "is a pretty decent tailwind." In general, individuals believed that, given the economy's continued fall in activity or growth, "things were fairly balanced, or maybe even positioning for more downside risks." However, it appears that things have become more robust.

In other news, Microsoft saw a gain of about 1%, temporarily pushing its market worth above $3 trillion. The market value of Facebook's parent company, Meta, increased by 1.4% to surpass $1 trillion.

These gains reinforced the 2024 mega-cap tech sector's stellar performance, which drove the S&P 500 to all-time highs and validated the start of a new bull market. Communication services and information technology firms bolstered the broad index on Wednesday, up 1.2% and 0.8%, respectively.

Apart from technology, AT&T's stock dropped almost 3% due to lower-than-expected results. Following the release of dismal first-quarter forecasts and the announcement of bad fourth-quarter results, DuPont De Nemours saw a 14% decline.

After the bell, traders will continue to be focused on Tesla, Las Vegas Sands, and IBM's earnings releases. According to FactSet, over 71% of the more than 16% of S&P 500 businesses that have released quarterly financials this earnings season have exceeded Wall Street estimates.

The creator of the Blue Chip Daily Trend Report, Larry Tentarelli, declared, "The markets are very bullish." Furthermore, "the response to earnings is the crucial factor right now."

Title: Attempted kidnapping in Glendale: Neighbor shares footage
Description:
Glendale Police officers responded to the area of 43rd and Peoria avenues on the morning of Jan. 26 after the girl made a report "that an unknown adult male had attempted to grab her as she walked to school."

Investigators obtained and reviewed video footage. They found the suspect and his car seen in the footage.

37-year-old Joseph Ruiz was arrested on suspicion of attempted kidnapping charges.

A neighbor says the attempted kidnapping of the young girl was captured on a surveillance camera.

Title: Why did China create the 22 (pilot) Free Trade Zones?
Description:
China launched the (Pilot) Free Trade Zones in 2013 to spur foreign direct investment. Initially in Shanghai, followed by other regions, these Bonded Zones offer customs duty exemptions and tax benefits for stored goods. The zones, now totaling 22, include the recent one in Xinjiang, supporting the Belt and Road Initiative. The Shanghai (Pilot) Free Trade Zone, a pioneer, covers 120 sq km in Pudong with diverse sectors like finance and manufacturing. It streamlines trade, attracts foreign companies, and serves as a testing ground for economic reforms.

Title: British National Ian J Stones Jailed for Spying in China
Description:
Ian J Stones, a British national, was sentenced to five years in jail for spying in 2022. Stones was accused of committing the "crime of illegally obtaining intelligence for overseas actors". Despite Stones' appeal, the sentencing was upheld in September, as disclosed during a Mofa briefing. Stones had a four-decade-long career in China, working with major US firms (like General Motors and Pfizer). 

About 15 years ago, Stones established a Beijing-based investment management consulting firm. Mofa spokesman Wang Wenbin stated that the court strictly followed the law in trying the case, ensuring various legitimate rights and arranging for British officials to visit and attend the trial. Stones' daughter claimed that embassy officials and one family member were allowed to witness one hearing but not the actual trial. 

They were also not permitted access to legal documents related to the case. Stones' daughter alleged that her father, initially healthy during detention, received inconsistent medical care and poor nutrition, leading to severe and life-threatening injuries. British Embassy staff have been able to visit Stones every four to six weeks, but there were long periods with no news and no consular visits allowed. 

China has been increasingly publicizing cases of alleged espionage by Western countries, launching public campaigns to raise awareness of foreign spying and urging people to report any suspicious activity. The UK government maintains a policy of neither confirming nor denying claims related to intelligence issues.

Il premier slovacco #RobertFico ha mantenuto la promessa fatta un paio di mesi fa e ha istituito la figura che indagherÃ  sulla gestione pandemica dei governi dell'era Covid. L'annuncio ufficiale Ã¨ al #Senato: "Diremo all'opinione pubblica cosa Ã¨ successo durante il Covid".
Chi si occuperÃ  di verificare cos'Ã¨ accaduto in Slovacchia, soprattutto dal punto di vista economico, molto discusso, sarÃ  Petrovi KotlÃ¡rovi, che la stampa estera etichetta prontamente. "Un noto no vax e cospiratore" sarÃ  il capo di quella Commissione che invece in Italia fa fatica da mesi a partire. Il premier Fico non ha aspettato troppo. Eletto il 30 settembre scorso, ha da subito incontrato la resistenza della stampa occidentale, che lo ha definito "putiniano", "filorusso" e "nazionalista". E da subito aveva parlato di questo ambizioso progetto in cui ora rinnova la fiducia. 

"Sono convinto che il suo lavoro porterÃ  risultati, che analizzeremo e pubblicheremo".
Fico non si trattiene perÃ² dal lanciare un feroce attacco e una dura accusa a #UnioneEuropea, von der Leyen, opposizione e governi precedenti. "I governi che si sono succeduti dal 2020 - dice in Senato - non erano in grado di gestire la situazione. Hanno guardato solo al profitto economico e hanno cercato di inchinarsi alle aziende farmaceutiche da cui hanno acquistato enormi quantitÃ  di dispositivi medici inutili e vaccini". Della gestione europea "non voglio neanche piÃ¹ parlarne". Fico aveva infatti anche condannato il noto trattato sanitario internazionale dell'OMS, annunciando che la Slovacchia non avrebbe dato il suo appoggio.

grande acquisto di vaccini nella storia della Commissione europea, quando si Ã¨ scambiata messaggi di testo segreti con il direttore della Pfizer. Noi non sapremo davvero mai la veritÃ  su quale gioco facessero le case farmaceutiche e chi davvero abbia organizzato tutto questo circo intorno al Covid".

Poi l'accusa a quei stessi governi che avevano imposto il lockdown ai non vaccinati.
"I governi precedenti hanno fallito con il Covid: hanno 21.000 morti tra le mani", il che si ricollega alla sua frase d'apertura, rivolta ai presenti in aula: "Avete letto le statistiche sull'aumento dei decessi per effetti avversi a causa delle vaccinazioni?".
